    {
        "content": "<p>Is it enough that the fibration <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span></span></span> has each fiber a (cancellative) monoid in order for this to be true? Or some other condition is necessary?</p>",
        "id": 308938775,
        "sender_full_name": "fosco",
        "timestamp": 1668068575
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I forget if Christina and Joe studied discrete monoidal fibrations in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1809.00727\">their paper</a>.   It'd be good to ask them.</p>",
        "id": 308955666,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1668075027
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We didn't bring up discreteness, but of course everything we did applies to that case. The thing we didn't consider was closedness. It did cross our minds, but the most obvious route didn't seem right, so we didn't pursue it.</p>",
        "id": 309012302,
